\begin_layout Standard
There is a finite-basket of products 
\begin_inset Formula $\{c_{1},c_{2},...,c_{m}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Which have varied prices i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=p(c_{i},k_{i})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a variable denoting the class of the product.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 can choose any or all (
\begin_inset Formula $h\le m)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 products -
\begin_inset Formula $\{c_{1},c_{2},...,c_{m}\}$
\end_inset

.
 While performing this selection, the consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is subject to the income constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum q_{h}=q_{j}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the given constraint for every consumer).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The revealed preference theory implies existence of relations 
\begin_inset Formula $yRx$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

) such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\epsilon S_{u}(x)=\{z\epsilon K|u(z)\ge u(x)\}$
\end_inset


