\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The utility function is for a choice 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{c_{j}}=\{c_{1},c_{2},...c_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\overrightarrow{c})$
\end_inset

- which would be maximised by every consumer for their own constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Given choices 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{c_{j}}$
\end_inset

 for consumers 
\begin_inset Formula $j\epsilon N$
\end_inset

, we therefore need to find a utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\overrightarrow{c})$
\end_inset

 so that the error between  
\begin_inset Formula $argmin(-u(\overrightarrow{c}))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{c}$
\end_inset

 itself is minimal.
 The approach one can use is to choose a general function (e.g.
 Cobb-Douglas) and use polynomial optimization to find parameters corresponding
 to optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we use Cobb-Douglas utility function : 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n})=\Pi x_{i}^{\alpha_{i}}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $argmin(-u(\overrightarrow{c}))=argmin(-ln(u(\overrightarrow{c})))=argmin(-\sum\alpha_{i}ln\ x_{i})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

